Furthermore, the longtime diffusion of ROS prior access to intracellular organisms probably weaken the cytotoxic damage to cancer cells due to the short lifetime of ROS [65–67]. Mitochondria are one of the most important intracellular organelles for cellular energy production, which are also crucial regulators in cell apoptosis. The direct damage and destruction of mitochondria would promote the programmed cell apoptosis rapidly [68–70]. Thus, the precise mitochondria-specific PDT is promising to kill cancer cells more efficiently than non-targeted PDT. Herein, mitochondria, which are widely distributed in cytoplasm, are chosen as the therapeutic target in current work. Tetramethylrhodamine-5-isothiocyanate (TRITC) [71–73], was selected as a mitochondria-targeting fluorescent probe to covalently decorate hybrid nanoparticles of UCNP and GQD, affording UCNP-GQD/TRITC nanoparticles. In order to enhance the distance-dependent energy transfer efficiency, GQD were covalently modified on the surface of UCNP via amide linkages, followed by surface chemical modification with TRITC. The mitochondria targeting in-situ 
                     1O2 burst could trigger instant mitochondrial damage to initiate the programmed cell apoptosis, exhibiting much more remarkable therapeutic effect than non-targeted counterparts based on in vitro and in vivo explorations (Scheme 1
                     ).

In contrast, the latter two groups treated with UCNP-GQD and UCNP-GQD/TRITC in the presence of 980 nm laser irradiation showed much slower growth rates, indicating excellent tumor inhibition efficacy with the tumor inhibition rate to be ∼70.2%, ∼75.3%, respectively (Fig. 6
                        a and b, Table 1
                        ). The digital photos of excised tumors from representative mice visually displayed that the tumor sizes treated with UCNP-GQD and UCNP-GQD/TRITC with irradiation were smaller than other groups (Fig. 6c). Furthermore, upon NIR irradiation, UCNP-GQD/TRITC exhibited much better tumor inhibition effect than UCNP-GQD due to the intrinsic mitochondrial targeting potency and instantly drastic damage to mitochondria to initiate the programmed apoptosis of tumor cells.
